Anonymous Wed 28 Feb 2024 23:25:06 No.63644490 Report
Quoted By: >>63644532 >>63644711
>>63644005
>Minor actions should be consistent with major actions
I mean, you can have a character change throughout a story. It doesn't have to be a major change, like 'optimistic farm boy becomes jaded antihero', but you can have them do uncharacteristic things once they've been challenged.
For example, a character can be ordered to kill an innocent person, and they can start with saying 'fuck no that's against my morals', before they get into constant bloody conflict that starts to imprint on them the necessity of survival over morality. Later, they can start doing morally dubious things with nothing more than a little complaining, and it would still be "in character". This is especially common in war. While a lot of war stories like to play up a veteran coming home all fucked up emotionally, the reality of it is that you can have a meek and passive person go into war, then turn into a monster who shoots prisoners and doesn't feel a thing, then they come back home and no one can really tell the difference besides a slight demeanor change. 'All quiet on the western front' did this very well.
So for your hypothetical character, they can be a regular hoe, but if they live in an environment of shit boots who kill without reason, they could very well just snap one day and become as shitty as the murderers around them.

>treat writing like a job
That's terrible advice to give to a hobbyist writer and even worse advice to give to someone starting out. Like with any other hobby you should do it because the simple act of the thing gives you joy, if you have to force yourself to write everyday then you have a one way trip to burnout city. Professional writers can pump out those words because there's a profit motive involved and behind that there's also a genuine love of the craft. If someone's starting out and after the first couple stories they still hate writing then forcing themselves to grind out thousands of more words isn't going to flip some magic switch in their brain and make them enjoy it. Like with any other venture in life you should give it an honest try and if you don't like it, you don't like it.
